               <msContents>
                  <summary>According to the opening of this volume entitled here, <title>Jung-i Kalām-i
                     Isti‘mālī</title> (Anthology of Customary Sayings), also known as the <title>Jung-i Quṭb Shāhī</title>, the author <persName></persName> Quṭb Shāhī-era minister
                     <persName role="pat" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/6528564"
                        key="person_6528564">Muḥammad Sa‘īd (d. 1663)</persName>, known as <addName
                           type="honorfic" role="com pat" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/6528564"
                           key="person_6528564">Mīr Jumlā</addName>, dedicated by  encyclopedic
                     anthology for the ruler <persName role="dte" key="person_44546161"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/44546161">Sultān ‘Abdallāh Quṭb Shāh (b. 1614, r.
                        1626–1672)</persName>, culled from various sources including the
                        <title>Makārim al-Akhlāq</title> ('Noble Manners', see Rylands <ref
                        target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7184"><idno>Persian MS
                           680</idno></ref>) by <persName role="ant" key="person_97601210"
                        ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/97601210/">Ṭabarsī (d. 1153)</persName>, the
                        <title>Iḥyà ‘Ulūm al-Dīn</title> ('Revival of Religious Sciences') by
                        <persName role="ant" key="person_31996761"
                        ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/31996761/">Muḥammad al-Ghazzālī (d.
                        1058-1111)</persName>, (and probably the author's abridged Persian
                     translation entitled <title>Kīmiyā-yi Saʻādat</title> 'Alchemy of Happiness',
                     see Rylands <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6715"
                           ><idno>Persian MS 231</idno></ref> to <ref
                        target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6719">235</ref>),
                        <title>Kashf al-Ghummat</title> (Lifting of Sadness) by <persName role="ant"
                        key="person_79259058" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/79259058">al-Irbīlī (d.
                        1293)</persName>, <title>Rabīʿ al-Abrār</title> ('Springtime of the Just',
                     see Rylands <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_13942"
                           ><idno>Arabic MS 242</idno></ref>) by <persName role="ant"
                        key="person_90071384" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/90071384/">al-Zamakhsharī
                        (d. 1144)</persName>, and <title>Rasā’il</title> ('Treatises') by the
                        <persName role="ant" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/149871335/"
                        key="person_149871335">Ikhwān al-Safā’</persName> or 'Brotherhood of
                     Purity'. Subjects encompass the religious sciences, ethics, philosophy, polite
                     learning and the interpretation of dreams, followed by a <q xml:lang="en"
                        >Supplement</q>, described as a separate epistle but comprised of five
                     chapters on five words connected to kingship, followed by a conclusion. </summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_457-item1">
                     <author role="com att" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/6528564" key="person_6528564">
                        <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Muḥammad Sa‘īd (d.
                           1663)</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">محمد سعيد</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_6967">Jung-i Kalām-i Istiʿmālī</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_6967">جنگ کلام استعمالی</title>
                     <title type="alt" xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_6967">Jung-i Kalām-i
                        Muḥammad Sa‘īd</title>
                     <title type="alt" xml:lang="fa" key="work_6967">جنگ کلام محمد سعيد</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="basmalla"><locus from="77b" to="77b"> برگ ۷۷پ
                           (folio 77b):</locus> ابتدای کلام بنام خداوندی سز است که ابتدای هر چیز
                        ازوست و انتهای سخن بکلام قادری سزآواراست که بازگشت همه بدوست ... </incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa"><locus from="76a" to="76a"> برگ ۷۶ر (folio
                           76a):</locus> یا رب دعای خسته دلان مستجاب کن و از جمله اتفاقات خسنه اینمه
                        روزی که امر عالی باانتخاب تاریخ حکما و در سخنان از کلام اکابر و فضلا شرف
                        صدور یافت کلمهٔ انتخاب موافق تاریخ کتاب بود و عون ثانی الحال مامور شد که آن
                        منتخب را باخلاق و سیر پادشاهان صورت اتمام در اخلاق پادشاهی مطابق آمد </explicit>
                     <colophon xml:lang="ar"><locus from="76a" to="76a"> برگ ۷۶ر (folio
                           76a):</locus> اللهم ايده بمريد التاديب وايده بكمال التهيد والنصره على
                        الاعداء واحفظ في الفراء والسراء بمحمد وآله تمت تمام شد بتاريخ ١٣ شهر ذو
                        الحجه سنه ١٨</colophon>
                     <colophon> The compiler describes in the introduction and again in the explicit
                        on folio <locus from="76a" to="76a">76a</locus>, how <persName role="dte"
                           key="person_44546161" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/44546161">Sultān
                           ‘Abdallāh Quṭb Shāh (b. 1614, r. 1626–1672)</persName> noted the year of
                        completion of the work numerically corresponds with the word <hi
                           rend="italic">intikhāb</hi> (choice), equivalent to <date
                           calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1644" to="1645">1054 AH (1644-45
                           CE)</date>, hence directs it be used as a chronogram for these <hi
                           rend="italic">muntakhab</hi> (selections). However, the colophon then
                        cryptically states it was completed on <q xml:lang="en">13 Ẕū-al-Ḥijjah year
                           18</q>. Prior interpretation of that as a Christian date (i.e. 1800)
                        seems incongruent with an Islamic month. Since only the kings of Awadh
                        (Oude) previously owned the volume, with the seal of the last king,
                           <persName type="person" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/305855167"
                           role="fmo seal" key="person_305855167">Wājid ‘Alī Shāh r.
                           1847–1856)</persName>, impressed over paper repairs, the number may
                        possibly indicate the regnal years of either <persName key="person_36047908"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/36047908/">Shuja‘ al-Dawlah</persName> or
                           <persName ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/4638161696247516120008/"
                           key="person_4638161696247516120008">Aṣaf al-Dawlah</persName>.
                        Alternatively, it may also possibly indicate <date cert="medium"
                           calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1804-03-25">1218 AH (hence 25 Mar. 1804
                           CE)</date>, although the deteriorated condition suggests an earlier date
                        more likely. No historical account records Muḥammad Sa‘īd completing such an
                        anthology, hence the work may be altogether spurious. </colophon>
                     <note>The main text begins on folio <locus from="77b" to="77b">77b</locus>
                        (i.e. f. 1a), with the dedication to <persName role="dte"
                           key="person_44546161" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/44546161">Sultān
                           ‘Abdallāh Quṭb Shāh (b. 1614, r. 1626–1672)</persName> followed by praise
                        of the compiler <persName role="com att" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/6528564"
                           key="person_6528564">Muḥammad Sa‘īd (d. 1663)</persName> by his title
                           <addName type="honorfic" role="com pat"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/6528564" key="person_6528564">Jumlāt
                           al-Mulk</addName>. After Chapter Four, subsequent headings omitted, and
                        the first page of volume 2 appears missing. Note that Micheal Kerney
                        previously identified the title as <title>Jang-i Kalām</title> (War of
                        Words) and dated the volume to 1800 based upon based upon the inscription on
                        the <locus from="ia" to="ia">first right flyleaf a side (f. ia)</locus>. A
                        prior record also bore the title <title>Jung-i Kalām-i Ismā'īlī</title>
                        (Anthology of the Words of Ismā‘īl); however, the actual title appears to be
                           <title>Jung-i Kalām-i Isti‘mālī</title> (Anthology of Customary
                        Sayings).</note>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>The following represents a preliminary list of the work's chapters and
                        their place in the manuscript.</note>
