                           </dimensions></p>

                        <condition>Binding sound but very tight. White salts (spew) on the leather
                           doublures probably resulting from prolonged exposure to
                           moisture.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <summary>Three library seals of the kings of <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001502" key="place_7001502">Awadh
                           (Oude)</placeName>, intaglio-carved in nasta‘līq script in two stacked
                        lines impressed in <material>vermilion</material> on the first and last
                        folios of the volume, <locus from="77b" to="77b">77b</locus> and <locus
                           from="76b" to="76b">76b</locus> of the supplement, with a second smaller
                        rectangular seal impressed in <material>black</material> on folio <locus
                           from="77a" to="77a">77a</locus>.</summary>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label rend="bold">1:</label>
                           <ref
                              target="https://image.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/iiif/MS-PERSIAN-00457-001-00508.jp2/1423,1047,943,663/full/0/default.jpg"
                              >Rectangular seal impression</ref> of the library of <persName
                              role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/265857376" key="person_265857376"
                              >Nāṣir al-Dīn Ḥaydar Shāh (b. 1803, r. 1827–1837)</persName> dated
                              <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1828" notAfter="1829"> 1244
                              AH (1828–29 CE)</date>, inscribed with his title <addName
                              type="epithet" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/265857376"
                              key="person_265857376">Sulaymān Jāh</addName>:</p>
                        <decoNote type="stamp" subtype="inscription"><p><quote xml:lang="fa"> خوش
                                 است مهر کتبخانه سلیمان جاه * بهر کتاب مزین چو نقش بسم الله،
                                 ١٢۴۴</quote></p>
                           <p>
                              <quote xml:lang="en"><hi rend="italic">Khvush ast muhur-i
                                    kitābkhānah-'i Sulaymān Jāh bahr-i kitāb; muzayyin chaw naqsh-i
                                    basmallah</hi>, <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                                    notBefore="1828-07-14" notAfter="1829-07-02">1244
                                 </date></quote> (<quote xml:lang="en">The seal of the library of
                                 Sulaymān Jāh is good; it embellishes the book like the design of a
                                    <hi rend="italic">basmallah</hi>, <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                                    notBefore="1828-07-14" notAfter="1829-07-02"
                              >1244</date></quote>).</p>
                           <p><dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                                 <height>17</height>
                                 <width>37</width>
                              </dimensions></p></decoNote>
                     </seal>

                     <seal>
                        <p><label rend="bold">2:</label>
                           <ref
                              target="https://image.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/iiif/MS-PERSIAN-00457-001-00508.jp2/1191,2078,1135,1463/full/0/default.jpg"
                              >Rectangular seal surmounted by the royal emblem of Awadh</ref>, of
                              <persName role="fmo" key="person_9680150325559110090006"
                              ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/9680150325559110090006/">Amjad ‘Alī Shāh
                              (b. 1801, r. 1842–1847)</persName> dated <date
                              calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1844-01-22" notAfter="1845-01-09"
                              >1260 AH (1844–45 CE):</date></p>
                        <decoNote type="stamp" subtype="inscription"><p><quote xml:lang="fa">ناسخ هر
                                 مهر شد چون شد مزین بر کتاب * خاتم امجد علی شاه زمان عالیجناب،
                                 ١٢٦٠</quote></p>
                           <p><quote xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc"><hi rend="italic">Nāsukh har muhur shud
                                    chun shud muzayyin bar kitāb; khātim-i Amjad ‘Alī Shāh zamān-i
                                    ‘Ālījanāb</hi>, <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                                    notBefore="1844-01-22" notAfter="1845-01-09">1260</date></quote>
                                 (<quote xml:lang="en">Every [prior] seal became cancelled since the
                                 book became embellished by the seal of Amjad ‘Alī Shāh in the era
                                 of his Sublime Majesty, <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                                    notBefore="1844-01-22" notAfter="1845-01-09"
                              >1260</date></quote>).</p>
                           <p><dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                                 <height>53</height>
                                 <width>45</width>
                              </dimensions></p></decoNote>
                     </seal>
                     <seal>
                        <p><label rend="bold">3:</label>
                           <ref
                              target="https://image.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/iiif/MS-PERSIAN-00457-001-00508.jp2/2478,1079,719,1047/full/0/default.jpg"
                              >Rectangular seal surmounted by the royal emblem Awadh</ref>, of
                              <persName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/305855167" role="fmo"
                              key="person_305855167">Wājid ‘Alī Shāh (1822–1887), King of Awadh (r.
                              1847–1856)</persName> dated <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                              notBefore="1846" notAfter="1847">1262 AH (1846–47 CE)</date>:</p>
                        <decoNote type="stamp" subtype="inscription"><p><quote xml:lang="fa"> خاتم
                                 واجد علی سلطان عالم بر کتاب * ثابت و پر نور بادا تا فروغ آفتاب،
                                 ١٢۶۲ </quote></p>
                           <p><quote xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc"><hi rend="italic">Khātim-i Wājid ‘Alī,
                                    Sulṭān-i ‘Ālam bar kitāb, s̄abit va pur nūr bādā tā farūgh-i
                                    āftāb</hi>, 1262</quote> (<q xml:lang="en">The seal of Wājid
                                 ‘Alī, Sulṭān of the World, upon the book shall be permanent and as
                                 bright as sunlight, <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                                    notBefore="1844-01-22" notAfter="1845-01-09">1262 AH [1847
                                    CE]</date></q>).</p>
                           <p><dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                                 <height>41</height>
                                 <width>26</width>
                              </dimensions></p></decoNote>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label rend="bold">4:</label> Also on folio <locus from="77a" to="77a"
                              >1a</locus>, bottom, <ref
                              target="https://image.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/iiif/MS-PERSIAN-00457-001-00007.jp2/2012,5428,431,567/full/0/default.jpg"
                              >below the word <quote xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc"><hi rend="italic"
                                    >taḥvīl</hi></quote>, a rectangular <material>black </material>
                              seal impression</ref>, intaglio carved in nasta‘līq script, stacked in
                           two lines, single-ruled, of former owner or associate possibly named
                              <persName cert="medium" role="fmo asn">Nīnkā Bayg Khān</persName>
                           dated <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1814-12-14" to="1815-12-02"
                              >1230 AH (1814–15 CE)</date>:</p>
                        <decoNote type="stamp" subtype="inscription"><p><quote xml:lang="fa"> نینکا
                                 بیگ خان بندهٔ حسین، ١٢۳۰ </quote></p>
                           <p><dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                                 <height>13</height>
                                 <width>14</width>
                              </dimensions></p></decoNote>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin> Possibly <origPlace cert="medium"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001561">Lucknow</origPlace>; dated
                        <date cert="medium" calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1804-03-25">13
                        Ẕū-al-Ḥijjah, <q xml:lang="en">year 18</q>, possibly corresponding with 1218
                        AH (hence 25 Mar. 1804 CE)</date>. <note>The date appears unusual, and while
                        an inscription on the front flyleaf indicates it is a Christian year 18, it
                        may indicate 1218 AH or the regnal years of the Awadh (Oude) rulers
                           <persName key="person_36047908" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/36047908/"
                           >Shuja‘ al-Dawlah</persName> or <persName
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/4638161696247516120008/"
                           key="person_4638161696247516120008">Aṣaf al-Dawlah</persName>.</note>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance><p>Previously owned or inspected by an unidentified person named
                           <persName cert="medium" role="fmo asn seal" key="person_f6940">Nīnkā Bayg
                           Khān</persName>, as per his seal impression on folio <locus from="1b"
                           to="1b">1b</locus> dated <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1814-12-14"
                           to="1815-12-02">1230 AH (1814–15 CE)</date>, possibly an assitant to the
                        royal library of <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001502"
                           >Awadh</placeName> during the reign of <persName type="standard"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/2049153653237255900003"
                           key="person_2049153653237255900003">Ghazī al-Dīn Ḥaydar Shāh, r.
                           1818–27</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Definitely held in the royal library of <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001502">Awadh</placeName> in
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001502"
                           key="place_7001502">Awadh (Oude)</placeName>, as indicated by dated
                        library notations on folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus>, and seal
                        impressions of the Kings of Awadh <persName type="person" role="fmo"
                           key="person_265857376" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/265857376"> Nāṣir
                           al-Dīn Ḥaydar Shāh (b. 1803, r. 1827–1837)</persName>, <persName
                           role="fmo" key="person_9680150325559110090006"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/9680150325559110090006"> Amjad ‘Alī Shāh (b.
                           1801, r. 1842–1847)</persName>, and <persName type="person"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/305855167" role="fmo seal"
                           key="person_305855167">Wājid ‘Alī Shāh (b. 1822, r.
                        1847–1856)</persName>, then presumably looted during India's First War of
                        Independence, when British soldiers ransacked the Qaisarbagh palace and
                        library on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1858-03-15">15 March
                           1858</date>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently acquired by <persName type="supplied"
                     key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George
                     William Hamilton (1807-1868)</persName> who served in <placeName
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208"
                        >India</placeName>
                     <date calendar="#Gregorian" from="1823" to="1867"> from 1823 to 1867</date>,
                     latterly as Commissioner in <placeName
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535" key="place_7001535"
                        >Delhi</placeName>. He acquired over a thousand Indian and Persian
                     manuscripts, from which the <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/134857252"
                        >British Museum</orgName> purchased 352 from his widow, <persName key="person_f8470" role="fmo">Charlotte Logie Hamilton
                           (1817–1893)</persName>, now held in the <orgName
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/121814978">British Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </provenance>                  <provenance><p>
                        <persName type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                           key="person_97751058"> Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName>, purchased the remainder in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1868">1868</date>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr"
                           key="person_f6379">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> (1843–1908)
                        in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/"
                           key="person_9985420">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford
                           (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           when="1908">1908</date> to the <orgName role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/#John_Rylands_Library">John Rylands
                           Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
